node.text: O perfume. A história de um assassino

Com as limitações impostas pelo isolamento social, a leitura acabou tornando-se uma forte aliada dos chamados 'quarenteners'.

 "Esse momento de quarentena mostrou para as pessoas como é importante a gente aprender a estar consigo mesmo", afirma Pedro Pacífico, advogado de 27 anos, que mergulhou no mundo dos influenciadores digitais em 2017 ao criar o perfil @book.ster no Instagram. 

Ao longos dos últimos cinco meses, desde que a pandemia foi decretada pela Organização Mundial da Saúde, Pedro tem visto um grande crescimento em seu perfil literário na rede social, que agora já conta com mais de 260 mil seguidores. 

"A leitura é uma forma de você ter um momento para você. As pessoas estão tentando desenvolver hábitos mais saudáveis e a leitura é um deles. Isso talvez seja um efeito positivo do momento tão horrível que estamos vivendo", reflete. 

Quem acompanha as várias leituras que ele compartilha no Instagram todos os dias, nem imagina que esse hábito demorou para ser aprimorado. "Eu sempre gostei de ler desde criança, mas nunca fui um leitor tão assíduo. 

Eu ficava perdido na hora de escolher o livro, não sabia muito o que ler, não tinha referências". O depoimento de Pedro pode ser a realidade de muitas outras pessoas, que também se perdem na infinidade de possibilidades de leituras. 

"Eu acabava recorrendo sempre às listas de mais vendidos, achando que lá estariam os melhores livros", completa.

Quando descobriu a existência dos perfis literários na internet, passou a ser influenciado por eles, tanto a expandir o hábito da leitura, quanto a diversificá-la. "Comecei a ler livros clássicos, que eu tinha preconceito ou medo porque achava que seriam difíceis. 

Link na bio.

Fonte: Estadão

Hey you! Yeah...you! I know we're living in a pandemic right now but don't forget, it's really important to make sure you're getting your annual health visits in! I know a lot of doctors stopped doing these routine visits but most of them have begun again. Did you reschedule your appointment that might have been canceled during lockdown? Maybe, like me you didn't schedule it at all!? I finally got in for my annual well visit today, just before school starts back on Monday for me! Make sure you're taking care of you right now! It's probably more important than ever! Call your doctor! Call your dentist! Make that appointment you're putting off!

node.text: Wow you’re looking beautiful in yellow dress
I agree! This year has definitely brought out the simplicity of life

I am waving at Cooper in the window. He was watching me as I was walking back in the house, LOL. He's always like my little shadow and follows me everywhere I go. If you follow me on my Youtube channel (which you should ?, link in bio), Cooper is in most of my videos, especially the ones where I am working out, cleaning, or when I have Noah with me. ⁠
⁠
What this pandemic has taught me is that you have to be able to keep things simple to be happy. The luxuries that we are used to are gone and if you aren't right within and ain't going to win.⁠
⁠
What makes this time even more impressive is the ways that I have to raise Noah. I have had to take the natural approach. I am going outside more, walks, car rides. I don't know if I would be doing this if things were "normal" I wonder what type of baby he would have been.⁠
⁠
In today's blog post, I share with you how this pandemic has been teaching me about simple living and the benefits it had on my life and the life of my family. ⁠
⁠
What has the pandemic taught you?

Can I be real for a second? Being vulnerable on the internet is scary, but I have to get this off my chest. I like to keep things light and encouraging on here, but sometimes you just have to get in the trenches and talk it out. Starting a business in the middle of a pandemic is hard. On the business side, trying to figure out how build things from the ground up, make sure I'm adhering to state regulations, learning marketing, branding, social media. It's a lot. On the mental and emotional side there's trying to find locations that don't have a lot of people, knowing that right now people are struggling and not wanting to spend money, trying to make connections with people when creating connections right now is hard. It's exhausting. Add all the in between real life things- Homeschooling my littles, my college courses, responsibilities as a wife and stay at home mom, all the unrest in the world right now, watching my friends and family have to make difficult decisions. It's a lot! Some days I really struggle to keep it all together and thing running smoothly.
•
•
 So this is what it looks like. No fancy office with great natural light. No Pinterest worthy spaces. Just hiding in my room trying to get some work done. Leggings, no makeup, a messy bun because I'm 30 and still can't figure out how to do my hair.
•
•
I don't say all of this to sound like I'm complaining. One thing I've learned is that if I feel a certain type of way, chances are someone else does too. Is that you? Are you struggling with 2020 and all that it's brought? I need you to know that you're not alone. You're not crazy, and you're not dumb for feeling like this. This is hard stuff we're going through. 
•
•
My DMs are always open if you need to vent or cry or just want to say hey, me too. I want this space to be somewhere that you can be yourself and connect with other people, too! 
•
•
If you can relate to any of this, drop a comment and let me know. I'd love to chat with you. ??
•
•
•

node.text:
Did you know Covid may affect an unborn child's?? brain??

Hi!! I am Uchenna, a Speech Language Pathologist, with @littolingo. 

LIKE @LittoLingo for more tips on how to increase your kid’s communication. 

SHARE this post with other ??‍????‍?? parents ??‍???‍?? by TAGing ? them. 

Forbes Magazine reports “A pregnant ?? woman in France?? infected with the novel coronavirus during her final trimester had the virus spread through the placenta to her unborn child, leading to neurological complications in the infant days after birth. The mother was admitted in March exhibiting a severe cough and a fever, and after the baby ??was delivered through a cesarean section, he tested positive for the virus. 3?⃣ days after birth, the baby exhibited sudden symptoms like irritability and muscle spasms, and after 11 days, the researchers observed white matter injury in the brain.? The baby was discharged from the hospital ?after 18 days, and the researchers ??‍?noted that after 2 months, the child's health continued to improve??, including a reduction in neurological injuries.”

It is important you continue to use safe guidelines during this pandemic.

Up Above The World So High...

It has been years since I suffered a whiplash injury. Even till date, I don't have the luxury to tilt my head and look up straight. Broken ligaments of the neck take a decade to heal. Or even more. Yet, there was something about tonight's sky that made me try something I find very challenging. 
No rainbows on the horizon. No burst of twilight hues. Not a single star peeped at me. Just a naked rain-soaked electric line cutting across amorous clouds. Minimal but tenderly pregnant. Delicate and yet so dense.
I stared till my ligaments decided otherwise. Not only because the mouthful of sky looked surreal. But also since I knew when the ground beneath the feet seems tired of captivity, staring at the floating clouds can be the closest to tasting freedom during this pandemic

node.text:
This is part of a series I’m doing about our collective COVID experience...its working title is “The Unattainables”... it’s a reflection on who we are as consumers...what do we seek? What items provide comfort? Is comfort even possible... can it be purchased? Where do we seek comfort? Is it found in “the stuff”or perhaps in what we do with the stuff? ... and is that about our calculation of our worth? So much to ponder...
What do you seek during this pandemic experience? As I ponder that question with you, I want to send all the lovingkindness in my heart to each of you as we turn towards the Fall... more stepping into the not knowing, trusting in universal love to hold us... sending love to each of you, holding you in my heart...
.
.
.

node.text: Allow what’s meant to ruin you make you invincible. I feel like this has been the motto for my life, mostly because it’s had to be. I’ve been put through the motha fuckin RINGER and if I didn’t have this mentality I totally would have crumbled by now. I’ve been thinking about this quote a lot the last few days. If you watch my stories than you know that I am in a terrible situation when it comes to housing right now. Due to the pandemic we have to move like immediately, we didn’t get approved for the loan to buy the house since the landlord wants to sell, and the rental market is terrible. I had a mini breakdown yesterday. I started thinking about how I ALWAYS do everything by the book and things just don’t work out for me. When you are trying to break cycles of poverty, addiction, homelessness, it’s not as easy as “work hard and you will succeed”. I’ve spent my entire life working as hard as I can, getting all straight a’s, working multiple jobs, and still I always fall short because of something from my past. Both of my parents have passed away, so I don’t have anyone to help me co-sign for loans, or lend me a few dollars if I need it, or teach me how to build credit or apply for a mortgage. My mom let her addiction get the best of her and she started me off with terrible credit when I turned 18 by using my SSN to sign up for cards, gas and electric.. the list goes on. I’ve been trying to work off the disadvantages growing up in extreme poverty with addict parents my entire life.. and it’s fucking hard. My life has been full of struggles, unbelievable stories, things you only see in the movies.. and I could have let it ruin me. But I just let it fuel my fire. Some days I just want to throw in the towel, but then I think about what I’ve already been able to survive. You can get through ANYTHING with hope. It’s not as easy as “working hard”, and it won’t always be a straight path, but if you never give up on yourself, I promise you it will just make you more and more unbreakable every single time. Don’t let your past define you, always believe that you’re destined for more, have hope for your future and know that you are 100% THAT invincible ass bitch!

node.text:
#Repost @iyengaryoga_uk
• • • • • •
The IY(UK) Therapy Committee has created a video and compiled a booklet with a suggested yoga programme to support recovery from Covid-19. 

As we know, Covid-19 is a highly infectious disease caused by the coronavirus. Most people infected will experience a mild to moderate respiratory illness, whilst others will show no symptoms at all. However for some the effects are severe and longer lasting.

Our aim in this yoga programme is to play some role in aiding the process of recovery. By only requiring the use of mostly basic props and furniture, we have tried to make the poses as accessible as possible for everyone.

The programme was compiled thanks to advice and guidance from Abhijata Iyengar, Lois Steinberg, Gulnaaz Dashti, Stephanie Quirk, the IY(UK) Therapy Committee, IY(UK) teachers who have experienced the virus themselves, and decades of work by BKS Iyengar and Dr Geeta S. Iyengar in medical classes at RIMYI in Pune.

See the link in our bio to access the video and booklet, which are both freely available. Please consider donating a contribution towards this and future Iyengar yoga therapy resources ?

Thanks to all involved in creating the programme and to @adrienne_karmaspaceyoga for designing the e-book

location.address_json: {"street_address": "Vendome and Del Monte", "zip_code": "90026", "city_name": "Los Angeles, California", "region_name": "", "country_code": "US", "exact_city_match": false, "exact_region_match": false, "exact_country_match": false}

node.text:
Today’s stop on my pandemic Hollywood tour is for all you Hollywood history buffs (like myself) out there! It isn’t a house or a building....it’s a simple set of municipal steps called “The Music Box Steps” - named after the classic 1932 Laurel and Hardy comedy short called “The Music Box”!

The steps, which are the focal point of this hilarious film, still exist in the Silver Lake district of Los Angeles, near the Laurel and Hardy Park!! The steps are a public staircase that connects Vendome Street (at the base of the hill) with Descanso Drive (at the top of the hill), and are located at ‪923-925 North Vendome Street‬ near the intersection of Del Monte Drive. A plaque commemorating the film was set into one of the lower steps! 

If you’ve never seen this laugh-out-loud film it’s arguably the famous comedy duo’s most iconic work! The slapstick short’s most memorable scene is a string of gags involving the duo attempting to move a massive piano up a long flight of stairs. In short, they’re absolutely terrible at it. Lol 

FYI - Without a piano, these steps aren’t such a tough climb — it’s comprised of 133 steps with multiple landings.

This legendary short film comedy won the first Academy Award for Best Live Action Short (Comedy) in 1932. In 1997, the film was selected for preservation in the National Film Registry by the Library of Congress!

Fun facts - The crate that Stan Laurel and Oliver Hardy wrestle with was empty, but the one shown sliding down the staircase really did have an upright piano in it. As it careens down the steps muffled, discordant tones can be heard.

The idea for the film came to a Hal Roach comedy writer in 1927 when he passed a long flight of stairs in the Silverlake area of L.A. and thought it would be a good idea to have Stan Laurel and Oliver Hardy trying to move something heavy up them. 

This was Laurel and Hardy’s only Oscar-winning film together. “The Music Box” was one of Stan's' personal favorites. Stan kept this Oscar in his apartment in Santa Monica, and he called it ‘Mr. Clean’. ??? #filminglocation #themusicboxsteps #silverlake #laurelandhardy #hollywoodtour #pandemic2020 #socialdistancing #wearamask #tonymiros

node.text: Perfect, I was going to ask you about this tomorrow! ?? Xx
Perfect, I was going to ask you about this tomorrow! ?? Xx

With the current ‘new normal’ of wearing face masks whenever in public & for those who have to wear coverings all day, we are finding that our skin is feeling the strain. So lets have a look at why we are having such a reaction & what we can do to limit some of the damage!
 ?
The biggest issue with face masks is the condensation from our breath. This condensation creates a warm & moist environment; leading to blocked pores, bacteria growth and irritation. Inflammatory conditions such as Dermatitis, Psoriasis, Acne & Rosacea are irritated & flare ups are common. The tightness of the face coverings also create friction, rashes & in some instances, hives. One of the biggest issues of this new micro-climate is that it causes the skin to sweat more, whilst the masks simultaneously absorb the skins natural oils. Thus leaving our skin dry, producing excess sebum & sore/flaky.
 ?
If you are not a frontline (Healthcare) worker, then always use face coverings made from a breathable fabric (stay far away from synthetics), wash it regularly & try to limit any make up worn. TLC is paramount, so make sure you are supplying adequate hydration & then locking this in with an emollient – reapplication may be required multiple times throughout the day. The right facial oil may also be beneficial at this time to sooth certain conditions, keep the skin flexible & limit irritation. Also try to limit known skin irritants if you will be wearing a mask directly afterwards eg, acids, retinol, fragrance, tea tree/witch hazel.
?

node.text:
Good morning family! Y'all ok?⁣
⁣
Every wonder who the first Black Lawyer or elected official was was?? He was John Mercer Langston.⁣
⁣
Born December 14, 1829 in Louisa County, VA, Langston was a leader, diplomat, educator and believed to have been the first Black ever elected to public office in the United States.⁣
⁣
John passed the bar in Ohio in 1854. He was elected to the post of Town Clerk for Brownhelm, Ohio, in 1855. Langston was also the great-uncle of Langston Hughes, the famed poet of the Harlem Renaissance era. ⁣
⁣
"For the first two decades of the postwar era, Langston held prominent political and educational appointments. In 1868, he returned to Washington, DC, where he established the law department at Howard University, a new college founded to educate African Americans. In the early 1870s, Senator Charles Sumner of Massachusetts sought Langston's aid in drafting his Civil Rights Bill. In 1871, Langston received an appointment from President Ulysses S. Grant (for whom he had campaigned in 1868) to the District of Columbia Board of Health. Langston served as Howard University's dean from 1868 to 1875 and from 1874 to 1875 as vice president and acting president of Howard; however, he resigned from the university when the board of trustees failed to offer him a full term as president."⁣
⁣
- historyhouse.gov

node.text:
Did you know that we have a licensed drone pilot!? ?

With recent advances in technology, drones have made most tasks more efficient and effective, and home inspections are no exception.

Here are a few ways drones can make our inspections better:

1. Drone inspections are more thorough- with a drone we can observe all those difficult-to-access places. The roof of the home can have a plethora of nooks and crannies, and without a drone it’s hard to see some of the finer details. 

2. Drone inspections are more efficient- the drones ability to fly allows it to cover a broader area more quickly than a person with a ladder navigating steep slopes. 

3. Drones can provide an aerial overview of the property- this can come in handy for properties that come with a vast amount of acres and out buildings. This way you can see the condition of the buildings from above, the landscape features, placement of trees and shrubs and neighbors. 

Need an inspection on a roof our ladders can’t reach? Or an aerial video of your listing? Take advantage of our drone service today!

Schedule online ?? newleafinspections.com

node.text:
Data sekuen genom SARS-CoV-2 per 18 Agustus 2020?
?
Basis data GISAID (https://www.gisaid.org) memperlihatkan total genom SARS-CoV-2 yang telah disubmit per 18 Agustus 2020 sebanyak 82.224 sekuen yang berasal dari ratusan negara terjangkit COVID-19, termasuk Indonesia. Dari keseluruhan genom yang sudah disubmit, 92,25% digunakan untuk melakukan pengelompokkan atau klastering SARS-CoV-2 dalam klade S, L, V, G, GH dan GR. ?
?
Analisis pribadi menggunakan CoVSurfer dalam GISAID menunjukkan bahwa dari total 18 genom pasien Indonesia dihadapkan dengan genom referensi Wuhan memperlihatkan setidaknya 10 mutasi pada protein, salah satunya yang saat ini menjadi berita utama yaitu S D614G.?
 ?
Mutasi pada protein Spike D614G tersebut ditemukan pada 4 genom virus dari pasien Indonesia yaitu EPI_ISL_437188 dan EPI_ISL_458082  dari Surabaya serta EPI_ISL_511878 dan EPI_ISL_511879 dari Bandung. ?
?
@inbio_indonesia ?
?

node.text:
“Probably in the 1970s, my dad surprised my mother. He took one of the stones from their engagement ring and placed it in a band and bought two other stones to go with it. My mom wasn’t big on material things, but this band meant something to her because it showed how much my father loved her and cared for her.

My mother is from Tulsa, Oklahoma, and my dad was stationed in Tulsa during World War II. As the story goes, the barracks used to give dances or something like that. Then in comes my mom — beautiful, beautiful, beautiful. His face lit up when he saw her. 

When the war ended, my dad came back to Chicago. My grandma, his mother, owned a lot of property on the South Side. So my Dad sent for my mom and they came and lived in an apartment in my grandma’s building. They bought their first home in 1955 in Englewood.

My mother was the type of woman — she didn’t wait for my father to bring home the paycheck. My mother said, ‘Wait one minute. If something happens to your dad, then what will I do? I’m going to get out there and work too.’ 

She was a great wife. My father might have been the man of the house but my mother was the boss. And she taught my sister and I what it meant to be a woman — not just a woman, but a Black woman. To stand on your own two feet, to make your life worth something. To not depend on someone else to do for you when you can get out to do for yourself. 

This is the type of mother I had.”

WBEZ’s @nueli photographed Josette Merill, whose mother, Lillie Merrill, died of COVID-19 in April at the age of 98. Click the link in bio to read our full story about 50 Chicagoans who have lost relatives to COVID-19 — and the conditions that led to the pandemic's starkly disproportionate impact.

From 'Is my screen visible?' To 'Am I audible?' The Batch of 2020 surely heard these lines said aloud more than anyone. 

The worldwide pandemic and the subsequent lockdown affected the lives of students everywhere. In these tough and challenging circumstances, the ill-fated batch encountered many obstacles and underwent mental stress while coping up with the digitized learning platforms.

To gain more insights, tune into our latest blog 'Peeking Through An Uncertain Future: Batch of 2020.'

First Day of School !!!! 
4th Grade one year to remember for sure ! ?? Seeing all the kids with mask broke my heart just to know that our kids have to go through this pandemic. Having to wear their mask through the whole school day. Not to mention kids we’re not allowed to take backpacks just a brown bag with their lunch. All school supplies were provided by the school. We didn’t have to worry buying supplies this year. One very different year! 
All parents were giving specific rules and instructions when it came to kids attending school. 
I totally understand some parents own opinions and concerns but this is my kid and I do whatever I want !!!!! ....

Cerca de 500 indígenas Embera Katío y Embera Chamí, que huyen de la violencia en Chocó y Risaralda se encuentran acampando desde hace un mes en el Parque Tercer Milenio en el centro de Bogotá. La alcaldía ha amenazado con demandar a sus líderes por estar allí en medio de la pandemia, y el fin de semana hubo un intento fallido de albergar los en Corferias debido a que ese lugar es un hospital, no un albergue. Los indígenas exigen ayuda del estado, especialmente en términos de vivienda. Aseguran que la cuarentena les ha eliminado su forma de sustento, que es usualmente el trabajo informal en las calles.
.

node.text:
Conquered Montenegro 

If you are looking to travel during the pandemic I definitely recommend Montenegro as a safe destination.

We avoided the capital city and stuck to the coastline, where there were very few people and it was super easy to stay distanced.

Vegan food isn’t that easy to come by, so I recommend buying fresh supplies from a market and making your own food. Their fresh veg is delish anyway ??

It almost felt like we had the whole country to ourselves and it was an incredible experience seeing the country without tourists!

node.text:
Ramassez ici. Un rare contact social en cette période de distanciation, là où les commerçants et restaurateurs se réinventent.

Photographie:  Jérôme Bourque (Agence Icone)
___
Le 12 mars dernier, le Gouvernement du Québec tenait une première conférence de presse pour annoncer la fermeture de plusieurs services, et le début de ce qui allait être un grand confinement pour contrer la pandémie de COVID-19. ?

Dès lors, nous avons demandé à nos partenaires de longue date chez @agence_icone, ainsi qu’à certains de nos collègues, de capter pour nous les moments d’espoir comme de désolation, sachant qu’elles et ils sauraient en dégager une grande poésie.

À l’aube des six mois du début de cette étrange aventure, souffrante mais aussi empreinte d’une grande résilience, nous partageons avec vous chaque jours leurs tirages. ?

Participez vous aussi à cette documentation en répondant à la question du moment dans la section «Documentez la pandémie» du site uneheureaumusee.ca. ??‍??

Et abonnez-vous à notre fil Instagram pour découvrir ce regard exceptionnel sur ce que nous avons vécu! ?

node.text:
Economic impact of pandemic in India#Jaan vs Jahaan???

#This pandemic has taken the job of approx. 140 million people and salaries cut for many others.?

#This is the worst recession since independence as per CRISIL statement.?

#Life vs Livelihood?
Yes, this debate has played out in India during pandemic 2020. In a poll 64% of people agreed that saving a life is priority while 36% agreed economy restart is a priority.
Govt first view was "life" is priority. PM said "Jaan hai to jahaan hai". Later it changed to "Life and Livelihood" - "Jaan bhi jahaan bhi" since people had no source of Income and their view was if they would have something, then only they can save their lives.

Do share your opinion in the comments below "Jaan or Jahaan"?

The @iyengaryoga_uk Therapy Committee has created a video and compiled a booklet with a suggested yoga programme to support recovery from Covid-19. 

As we know, Covid-19 is a highly infectious disease caused by the coronavirus. Most people infected will experience a mild to moderate respiratory illness, whilst others will show no symptoms at all. However for some the effects are severe and longer lasting.

Their aim in this yoga programme is to play some role in aiding the process of recovery. By only requiring the use of mostly basic props and furniture, they have tried to make the poses as accessible as possible for everyone.

The programme was compiled thanks to advice and guidance from Abhijata Iyengar, Lois Steinberg, Gulnaaz Dashti, Stephanie Quirk, the IY(UK) Therapy Committee, IY(UK) teachers who have experienced the virus themselves, and decades of work by BKS Iyengar and Dr Geeta S. Iyengar in medical classes at RIMYI in Pune.

See the link in their bio to access the video and booklet, which are both freely available. Please consider donating a contribution towards this and future Iyengar yoga therapy resources ?

Thanks to all involved in creating the programme and to @adrienne_karmaspaceyoga for designing the e-book

Countries led by women had “systematically and significantly better” Covid-19 outcomes, research appears to show, locking down earlier and suffering half as many deaths on average as those led by men.

The relative early success of leaders such as Germany’s Angela Merkel, New Zealand’s Jacinda Ardern, Denmark’s Mette Frederiksen, Taiwan’s Tsai Ing-wen and Finland’s Sanna Marin has so far attracted many headlines but little academic attention.

The analysis of 194 countries, published by the Centre for Economic Policy Research and the World Economic Forum, suggests the difference is real and “may be explained by the proactive and coordinated policy responses” adopted by female leaders.

node.text:
?????? ? @akhiltalks ??? ????
.
Ever since COVID-19 pandemic has locked us in our homes, we’re desperately waiting for a solution that could end this mayhem. 

Recently, India’s Serum Institute announced that it will be commencing human trials of the Oxford-AstraZeneca vaccine (which will be called Covishield in India)  that is already in Phase III trials globally and awaiting government approvals. 

And now, reports have revealed that Phase II/III of the Oxford vaccine are commencing this week in India. The trials of Covishield vaccine will involve 1,600 people above the age of 18 years across 17 locations in Pune, Mumbai and Ahmedabad. Out of the 1600 test subjects, 400 will be tested for immune response whereas 1200 will be tested to understand the safety of the vaccine. This is by far the largest COVID-19 vaccine trial in the country. 

Reports also indicate that in Mumbai, the trials are being conducted at KEM and Nair hospitals. They have already started the preliminary procedures for the study. The medical institution will be conducting trials on 320 volunteers between the age group of 20 and 50 years. In total, the trial has around 1000 to 1,100 participants enrolled across five to eight locations. 

The vaccine has already undergone Phase I and II trials in the UK where it showed positive results. Preliminary trials revealed that the vaccine induces an antibody response in just 28 days -- similar to the patients who have recovered from COVID-19. A second booster shot of the vaccine spikes antibody response at an even higher level. All the blood samples of patients with a second booster shot revealed neutralising activity. 

?REUTERS

node.text:
#newsworthy
What: The findings of a country-wide antibody test done by Thyrocare, a national-level private laboratory suggest that approximately 25% or 1 in 4 Indians have antibodies which make them immune to Covid-19. (Though we don't know how long this immunity lasts)
?
Details of the findings: 24% of the two-lakh plus people tested across the country so far have antibodies. Around 29% of people in Delhi and 20% in Maharashtra have anti-bodies. Even within Mumbai and adjoining areas, this number ranges from 21% to 32% of people.
?
Related: Surveys done at the city level by various civic corporations and some research organisations (TIFR, IISER) also point to the same results. Pune is an outlier. A serosurvey in the city suggested that over 50% of the people have antibodies to Covid-19. 
?
Wait: India is still far away from herd immunity. That happens where 60-70% of the population has antibodies.
.
.

.

Repost from @spiritysol
•
Have mercy on the mamas
For we are carrying it all, and then some.
We’re schooling and working and praying and worrying. Juggling careers and calendars and  dishes and deadlines and math facts and marriages and mental health. 
We’re rising with the sun, trying our best to beat the day
Hoping to squeeze in just one more task 
So maybe tomorrow we’ll have room to breathe 
.
We’re filling all the roles and bending backwards, trying not to break with the weight of it all
.
Have mercy on the mamas 
Because we’re tired to the bone, touched out, and torn to pieces 
scraping pennies,
scrapping plans,
and starting from scratch 
trying to find our way through the unknown 
on a road that’s treacherous and tricky on even the brightest of days 
.
We’re making heart breaking decisions 
Weighing risks 
Wondering how to keep our babes happy and engaged and safe and whole. Wonderfing how the F we’re going to be full time moms and full time teachers while also working to keep food on the table. And maybe shower once or twice before Christmas. 
.
We’re treading water- keeping our eyes on the horizon and clinging to hope, even when there’s none in sight. 
.
So tonight, in your prayers, please hold all the mamas in your heart for just a moment. We are strong and we’ll make it, but we need all the grace and mercy we can get.

node.text:
Every year, floods in Assam affect hundreds of schools and disrupt the education ecosystem. This year, the floods have come at a time when the state was already battling a crisis that's impacting girls' education: the COVID-19 pandemic

Clearly, infrastructure and disaster resilience are critical areas that need swift action in the state. But we also need prompt gender inclusive policies to counter the effects of socio-cultural barriers to girls' education specifically, and to prevent the risks of child marriage, labour, trafficking, and abuse, which rise with economic constraints. 

Join YKA and @malalafund in a campaign to spread the message and demand gender-inclusive policies to ensure girls in Assam get #BackToSchool after braving the double whammy of the pandemic and the floods, this year.

#covid19 #pandemic2020 #covid19 #girlseducation #educationmatters #flood #assamflood #endchildlabour #endchildmarriage

Cybersecurity risks continue to impact individuals and companies around the world.

However, another security risk, the coronavirus pandemic, has led businesses to take an active role in understanding, identifying and protecting the sensitive parts of their organisation.

Many are even beginning to see the benefits of security as a business enabler.

Thank you to our panel of Dr. Aleksandar Valjarevic (VP Business Development at Help AG), Mossab Hussein (CSO and Co-Founder at SpiderSilk and Tarek Kuzbari (Regional Director Middle East & Turkey at @cybereason) for providing insight into the impact of COVID-19 on cybersecurity on our live webinar with @arabianbusiness.

Watch the full episode and learn about the key considerations you and your business need to know, today: bit.ly/RESTART_EP6

node.text:
N Koreans ordered by Kim Jong-un to hand over pet dogs for meat amid food shortages..!! ? 

Dogs, especially pet dogs, are family to the homes they belong. But try telling that to the eccentric leader of North Korea. If reports in the media are to be believed, North Korea is facing a food supply crisis and its controversial leader has reportedly ordered his people to hand over their pet dogs so they can be turned into meat for restaurants.
According to a report in the New Zealand Herald, the move by the North Korean leader Kim Jong-un is thought to be aimed at quelling the rising discontent among the public as the economic situation in the secretive country is crumbling and food shortages have become a huge worry.

node.text:
Habang pinapanood ko yung vlog ng #TeamLove kanina, grabe, nakakaiyak. Sana maka-recover sila soon, hindi lang sa #COVID19 kundi pati sa pagkawala ng Papa ni Bont. Yun talaga yung pinakamasakit kasi na part: yung mawalan ka ng loved one sa gitna ng pandemic. (I have a friend who lost a loved one, too. And I can imagine how hard it is para sa kanya. Tapos ako as a friend, wala man lang magawa para sa kanya, di ko sya mapuntahan.?)⁣
⁣
I agree dun sa sinabi ni @baninaybautista na kelangan alagaan yung mental health. Sa sitwasyon nya bilang sya ay asymptomatic COVID-19 patient, madali lang makayanan ng katawan nya na mapaalis ang virus sa katawan nya. Ang mahirap ay yung manatiling mentally healthy while dealing with her condition. Sana wag na sila masyado umiyak kasi the more na umiiyak sila, mas sisipunin sila. And the more na na-stress sila, mas hihina ang immune system nila. (Sinabi ko yan actually sa comment section, hoping mabasa nila.?)⁣
⁣
Sa lahat ng may pinagdadaanan ngayon, COVID related man yan o hindi, let's stay healthy and spiritually positive. Mahirap pero kakayanin natin yan. Tayo pa ba????⁣
⁣
Let's spread positivity despite all struggles. Sending my virtual hugs to everyone!?????⁣

node.text:
As COVID-19 death toll reaches 800K, there are still not specific medications to treat the disease. This means that particularly, vulnerable populations, like the elderly and those with chronic diseases, continue to experience some of the toughest complications. Scientists are looking into 4 main types of treatments that span from repurposed antiviral drugs to innovative antibody therapy. 
Please read our Society’s seventh “All About the Coronavirus” publication for a comprehensive treatment comparison and its local implications.

node.text:
We are as the flute, and the music in us is from thee;
we are as the mountain and the echo in us is from thee.
 We are as pieces of chess engaged in victory and defeat:
our victory and defeat is from thee, O thou whose qualities are comely!
 Who are we, O Thou soul of our souls,
that we should remain in being beside thee?
 We and our existences are really non-existence;
thou art the absolute Being which manifests the perishable.
 We all are lions, but lions on a banner:
because of the wind they are rushing onward from moment to moment.
 Their onward rush is visible, and the wind is unseen:
may that which is unseen not fail from us!
 Our wind whereby we are moved and our being are of thy gift;
our whole existence is from thy bringing into being.

These shots of partygoers at the Wuhan Maya Beach Water Park have been widely shared online as many parts of the world continue to battle the pandemic.

When the city's lockdown lifted in April, a small spike in cases saw authorities introduce a widespread testing programme for all 11 million residents. By July it was safe for cinemas and most public spaces to re-open. There's now no ban on public gatherings in Wuhan, which has not had a local coronavirus case since mid-May. (? Getty Images).

Hello gorgeous. If u don’t already know, this fabric mask is our latest merchandise. It is not regular merchandise, each reusable mask comes with a story of love, grit and resilience. @mangosteenjoy work with a community of mothers from the B40, Orang Asli and the refugee community to support their family during this tough time. 
Each reusable mask is WHO guideline compliant. They recently run a Big Give campaign by @100percentproject to give away free reusable mask to every student in the schools. To those who already received our fabric mask, great job! If you wish to continue support this project, get in touch with them, you are indirectly helping a family! We are in this together!

Chapter 2 level 5:
These images were shot in the streets of parow during my first ever food run. I noticed an influx of beggars in my area and realized that the food crisis in our country has become a way bigger deal than before lockdown. Nobody was allowed to feed homeless people via a soup kitchen, we weren't even able to stop and setup a table to dish soup as law enforcement would be an issue. Nobody was allowed to do anything except go to the grocery store and come back home. So what would happen to the homeless if people's weren't up and about like usual. #anc #lockdown #lockdownlevel5 #welcometosouthafrica #coronavirus #corona #pandemic2020 #ancestors #anc #postapartheid #blm #blmmovement #homeless #stayhome

node.text: You are too sweet!!! I know this will mean the world to my little!
@xcelente1 we were talking as a staff about pen pals! I think that idea could really be amazing in a year like this.

Pen pals. It could be voluntary, but when I was in grade school I loved having pen pals. Maybe link with another school and exchange info. The letter writing is good practice for penmanship, grammar, creative and critical thinking. It also adds a social element much needed in this lockdown world.

My hands may feel like they are going to fall off but I accomplished my goal: a post card written to each student in the school. They’ll go in the mail tomorrow and hopefully get kids excited about the coming school year even though we will be in distance learning. This is just one way to work on building connection and showing care. If anyone has more ideas to do the same, send them my way. #eaglecharterschool #pandemic2020 #wemissourstudents

Active Coping rjadi saat seseorang membuat keputusan dengan sadar untuk memperbaiki hidupnya. Contoh: mencari pertolongan professional saat merasa depresi. PoSiTiVE REFRAMING Ketika seseorang merubah situasi negatif menjadi situasi positif atau menemukan yang terbaik dari situasi yang buruk. node.text:
Sahabat, di masa adaptasi kebiasaan baru, para anak murid harus menghadapi dilema ketika belajar di rumah: tidak semua punya koneksi internet, tidak semua punya kemampuan untuk membeli peralatan elektronik yang menunjang.

Pak Kayafas Banafanu mengerti itu. Anak-anak muridnya di SDN Amsila, Kabupaten Kupang, tak semua punya kemampuan yang sama. Ia rela membuka kelas meski masih dalam masa pandemi. Semua protokol kesehatan ia ikuti. Pak Kayafas dengan tegas menasehati murid-muridnya untuk mengikuti peraturan yang sama, demi melindungi mereka.

Sahabat, kini saatnya kita ciptakan #SekolahAman, bukan hanya dari kondisi gedung kelas yang rusak, tetapi juga dari ancaman penyakit agar tak menyerang para pejuang hebat seperti Pak Kayafas. Bantu mereka dan sekolah-sekolah lainnya di Indonesia. Kunjungi alamat web yang tertera di gambar.

node.text:
March 15, 2020
Arrived in Vienna, Austria ?? on the 14th of March. With borders closed all around the heart of Europe, Austria ?? started taking strict measures day by day. 

It was quite interesting seeing the mood of a country change firsthand as a strict lockdown was implemented. When we arrived on the 14th the atmosphere was still very relaxed with kids and people walking all over the streets. By the next day, March 15th, a falafel wrap was the last hot meal I was able to buy that wasn’t from a supermarket...
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

node.text:
#Repost @drjenpsych_
???
What I’m learning even more is how we are literally embedded in one another’s worlds: we touch the same surfaces, we sit in the same trains, we breathe the same air. •
•
We also ritual together: we mourn together, we pray together, we cheer for musicians together, we eat ballgame crackerjacks together. When there’s obstacle to collective ritual, we ache in a glaring lack. •
•

Imagine how we can grow from this knowing. Imagine if we viewed hunger as contagious as a virus that doesn’t discriminate. Imagine if we never let one another starve for anything vital, ever again.
•
•
All my care and support, XO, Dr. Jen

Trying to stay positive. Because at the end of the day, I’m still standing here with all of my privileges. I am a healthy able body person. I didn’t lose my job during the pandemic. I am supported by my family and friends. I have an abundance of blessings. So while I am anxious about what my job will look like for the 2020-2021 school year (Im a school psychologist for those who didn’t know), I know that I have skills and talents that will be needed to support my team.  While my safety and health are priorities , so is keeping a perspective. Thanks for attending my TedTalk.

@eminaomi_  Por la seguridad de todos deberían.

Hoy es uno de esos días en los que ando deseando que todo vuelva a la normalidad. No es fácil vivir de este modo, se deben hacer sacrificios por nuestro bienestar y el de nuestra familia. El usar mascarrillas, gafas y/o guantes es solo un pequeño sacrificio que se puede tolerar, pero el tener que cuidarse a cada segundo para proteger a tus seres más allegados sí es duro. Y más aún cuando no todos tienen consciencia de la realidad a la que nos estamos enfrentando. Si fuera que todos respetaran las reglas, pues todo bien, pero lamentablemente no siempre es así. Ciertamente esto no será para siempre, pero debemos ser más conscientes con nuestros actos, más objetivos, estar bien informados con fuentes confiables, hacerle caso a los profesionales de la salud que verdaderamente están comprometidos con que toda esta situación acabe, informarnos de quienes tienen el conocimiento empírico y comprobado. Para así, de esa manera poder actuar con mayor sabiduría y empatía ante toda esta situación. ¿Qué nos cuesta hacer el sacrificio ahora de protegernos correctamente? Para fiestas y visitas habrá tiempo después. No esperemos a que sea demasiado tarde y tengamos que lamentarnos para darnos cuenta. Y si no tienes la capacidad de educarte y actuar con consciencia no expongas al que sí lo está haciendo.

node.text:
In order to function everyday and to have some sort certainty about the future we need some measure of security when it comes to earning a living. For a lot of us that means having a STABLE job. 

JOB security- implies that your job is safe for the foreseeable future and hopefully till retirement. It can provide a lot of benefits. It provides you with a steady income as long as your job is secure. Most people seek security because it is a simple way to earn a living, your employer has your job and income covered. The sad truth about this NO job is really safe anymore. 

INCOME security- can mean your income never comes from one single source, if one source fails you have other sources to tap into, and eventually replace the failed sources with new ones. You create  and are maintaining a portfolio of income streams. 

With the economy and employment conditions we are facing today i think its important to create income security. 

There are various ways to create income security, one of them is self employment, I myself chose to start a business so i could create that income security. With the pandemic going on and many people being laid off, myself included, i reevaluated my relationship with my job and decided it was time to make a change and fight for that income security and be apart of something that is recession proof. My favourite thing is being in control of my income, and the fact that its more secure then any other jobs i have had, i rather have all the power and my personal freedom instead. #income #streamsofincome #helpingothers #freedom #job #security #career #opportunity #security #stability #pandemic2020 #incomestreams #incomeopportunities #calgary #jobloss #searchforbetter
